{"$schema":"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/oasis-tcs/sarif-spec/master/Schemata/sarif-schema-2.1.0.json","version":"2.1.0","runs":[{"tool":{"driver":{"name":"Checkmarx One","version":"1.0","informationUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","rules":[{"id":"test missing - t:9160662952871655611 [Taken from query_id] (kics)","name":"test missing","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"edfs Value: The 'Dockerfile' does not contain any 'USER' instruction Excepted value: The 'Dockerfile' should contain the 'USER' instruction","markdown":"edfs \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eValue:\u003c/strong\u003e The 'Dockerfile' does not contain any 'USER' instruction \u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExcepted value:\u003c/strong\u003e The 'Dockerfile' should contain the 'USER' instruction"},"fullDescription":{"text":"edfs Value: The 'Dockerfile' does not contain any 'USER' instruction Excepted value: The 'Dockerfile' should contain the 'USER' instruction"},"properties":{"security-severity":"9.0","name":"test missing","id":"test missing - t:9160662952871655611 [Taken from query_id] (kics)","description":"edfs Value: The 'Dockerfile' does not contain any 'USER' instruction Excepted value: The 'Dockerfile' should contain the 'USER' instruction","tags":["security","checkmarx","kics"]}},{"id":"CVE-2019-1010022 (containers)","name":"Cve20191010022","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"GNU Libc current is affected by: Mitigation bypass. The impact is: Attacker may bypass stack guard protection. The component is: nptl. The attack vector is: Exploit stack buffer overflow vulnerability and use this bypass vulnerability to bypass stack guard. NOTE: Upstream comments indicate \u0026#34;this is being treated as a non-security bug and no real threat.","markdown":"GNU Libc current is affected by: Mitigation bypass. The impact is: Attacker may bypass stack guard protection. The component is: nptl. The attack vector is: Exploit stack buffer overflow vulnerability and use this bypass vulnerability to bypass stack guard. NOTE: Upstream comments indicate \u0026#34;this is being treated as a non-security bug and no real threat."},"fullDescription":{"text":"GNU Libc current is affected by: Mitigation bypass. The impact is: Attacker may bypass stack guard protection. The component is: nptl. The attack vector is: Exploit stack buffer overflow vulnerability and use this bypass vulnerability to bypass stack guard. NOTE: Upstream comments indicate \u0026#34;this is being treated as a non-security bug and no real threat."},"properties":{"security-severity":"9.0","name":"Cve20191010022","id":"CVE-2019-1010022 (containers)","description":"GNU Libc current is affected by: Mitigation bypass. The impact is: Attacker may bypass stack guard protection. The component is: nptl. The attack vector is: Exploit stack buffer overflow vulnerability and use this bypass vulnerability to bypass stack guard. NOTE: Upstream comments indicate \u0026#34;this is being treated as a non-security bug and no real threat.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2005-2541 (containers)","name":"Cve20052541","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Tar 1.15.1 does not properly warn the user when extracting setuid or setgid files, which may allow local users or remote attackers to gain privileges.","markdown":"Tar 1.15.1 does not properly warn the user when extracting setuid or setgid files, which may allow local users or remote attackers to gain privileges."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Tar 1.15.1 does not properly warn the user when extracting setuid or setgid files, which may allow local users or remote attackers to gain privileges."},"properties":{"security-severity":"9.0","name":"Cve20052541","id":"CVE-2005-2541 (containers)","description":"Tar 1.15.1 does not properly warn the user when extracting setuid or setgid files, which may allow local users or remote attackers to gain privileges.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2017-20229 (containers)","name":"Cve201720229","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"MAWK 1.3.3-17 and prior contains a stack-based buffer overflow vulnerability that allows attackers to execute arbitrary code by exploiting inadequate boundary checks on user-supplied input. Attackers can craft malicious input that overflows the stack buffer and execute a return-oriented programming chain to spawn a shell with application privileges.","markdown":"MAWK 1.3.3-17 and prior contains a stack-based buffer overflow vulnerability that allows attackers to execute arbitrary code by exploiting inadequate boundary checks on user-supplied input. Attackers can craft malicious input that overflows the stack buffer and execute a return-oriented programming chain to spawn a shell with application privileges."},"fullDescription":{"text":"MAWK 1.3.3-17 and prior contains a stack-based buffer overflow vulnerability that allows attackers to execute arbitrary code by exploiting inadequate boundary checks on user-supplied input. Attackers can craft malicious input that overflows the stack buffer and execute a return-oriented programming chain to spawn a shell with application privileges."},"properties":{"security-severity":"9.0","name":"Cve201720229","id":"CVE-2017-20229 (containers)","description":"MAWK 1.3.3-17 and prior contains a stack-based buffer overflow vulnerability that allows attackers to execute arbitrary code by exploiting inadequate boundary checks on user-supplied input. Attackers can craft malicious input that overflows the stack buffer and execute a return-oriented programming chain to spawn a shell with application privileges.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"DynamoDB NoSQL Injection - 17313707663830775501 (sast)","name":"DynamoDB NoSQL Injection","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The application relies on user inputs provided in \u0026#34;https://www.google.com/recaptcha/enterprise.js\u0026#34; in /frontend/src/hooks/use-recaptcha.ts at line 6 to construct a PartiQL query with \u0026#34;https://www.google.com/recaptcha/enterprise.js\u0026#34; in /frontend/src/hooks/use-recaptcha.ts at line 6.\n\n","markdown":"The application relies on user inputs provided in \u0026#34;https://www.google.com/recaptcha/enterprise.js\u0026#34; in /frontend/src/hooks/use-recaptcha.ts at line 6 to construct a PartiQL query with \u0026#34;https://www.google.com/recaptcha/enterprise.js\u0026#34; in /frontend/src/hooks/use-recaptcha.ts at line 6.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"The application relies on user inputs provided in \u0026#34;https://www.google.com/recaptcha/enterprise.js\u0026#34; in /frontend/src/hooks/use-recaptcha.ts at line 6 to construct a PartiQL query with \u0026#34;https://www.google.com/recaptcha/enterprise.js\u0026#34; in /frontend/src/hooks/use-recaptcha.ts at line 6.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"9.0","name":"DynamoDB NoSQL Injection","id":"DynamoDB NoSQL Injection - 17313707663830775501 (sast)","description":"The application relies on user inputs provided in \u0026#34;https://www.google.com/recaptcha/enterprise.js\u0026#34; in /frontend/src/hooks/use-recaptcha.ts at line 6 to construct a PartiQL query with \u0026#34;https://www.google.com/recaptcha/enterprise.js\u0026#34; in /frontend/src/hooks/use-recaptcha.ts at line 6.\n\n","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"Stored Command Injection - 12103191884388488012 (sast)","name":"Stored Command Injection","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The application\u0026#39;s update_existing_pull_request method calls an OS (shell) command with push_command, at line 548 of /openhands/resolver/send_pull_request.py, using an untrusted string with the command to execute.  \r\n\r\nThis could allow an attacker to inject an arbitrary command, and enable a Command Injection attack.\n\nThe attacker may be able to inject the executed command into the database, which is then retrieved by the application with loads, at line 17 of /openhands/resolver/io_utils.py, in the load_all_resolver_outputs method.\n\n","markdown":"The application\u0026#39;s update_existing_pull_request method calls an OS (shell) command with push_command, at line 548 of /openhands/resolver/send_pull_request.py, using an untrusted string with the command to execute.  \r\n\r\nThis could allow an attacker to inject an arbitrary command, and enable a Command Injection attack.\n\nThe attacker may be able to inject the executed command into the database, which is then retrieved by the application with loads, at line 17 of /openhands/resolver/io_utils.py, in the load_all_resolver_outputs method.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"The application\u0026#39;s update_existing_pull_request method calls an OS (shell) command with push_command, at line 548 of /openhands/resolver/send_pull_request.py, using an untrusted string with the command to execute.  \r\n\r\nThis could allow an attacker to inject an arbitrary command, and enable a Command Injection attack.\n\nThe attacker may be able to inject the executed command into the database, which is then retrieved by the application with loads, at line 17 of /openhands/resolver/io_utils.py, in the load_all_resolver_outputs method.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"9.0","name":"Stored Command Injection","id":"Stored Command Injection - 12103191884388488012 (sast)","description":"The application\u0026#39;s update_existing_pull_request method calls an OS (shell) command with push_command, at line 548 of /openhands/resolver/send_pull_request.py, using an untrusted string with the command to execute.  \r\n\r\nThis could allow an attacker to inject an arbitrary command, and enable a Command Injection attack.\n\nThe attacker may be able to inject the executed command into the database, which is then retrieved by the application with loads, at line 17 of /openhands/resolver/io_utils.py, in the load_all_resolver_outputs method.\n\n","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"Missing User Instruction - fd54f200-402c-4333-a5a4-36ef6709af2f [Taken from query_id] (kics)","name":"Missing User Instruction","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Always set a user in the runtime stage of your Dockerfile. Without it, the container defaults to root, even if earlier build stages define a user. Value: The 'Dockerfile' does not contain any 'USER' instruction Excepted value: The 'Dockerfile' should contain the 'USER' instruction","markdown":"Always set a user in the runtime stage of your Dockerfile. Without it, the container defaults to root, even if earlier build stages define a user. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eValue:\u003c/strong\u003e The 'Dockerfile' does not contain any 'USER' instruction \u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExcepted value:\u003c/strong\u003e The 'Dockerfile' should contain the 'USER' instruction"},"fullDescription":{"text":"Always set a user in the runtime stage of your Dockerfile. Without it, the container defaults to root, even if earlier build stages define a user. Value: The 'Dockerfile' does not contain any 'USER' instruction Excepted value: The 'Dockerfile' should contain the 'USER' instruction"},"properties":{"security-severity":"9.0","name":"Missing User Instruction","id":"Missing User Instruction - fd54f200-402c-4333-a5a4-36ef6709af2f [Taken from query_id] (kics)","description":"Always set a user in the runtime stage of your Dockerfile. Without it, the container defaults to root, even if earlier build stages define a user. Value: The 'Dockerfile' does not contain any 'USER' instruction Excepted value: The 'Dockerfile' should contain the 'USER' instruction","tags":["security","checkmarx","kics"]}},{"id":"Command Injection - 10979096389566260942 (sast)","name":"Command Injection","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The application\u0026#39;s  method calls an OS (shell) command with input, at line 46 of /openhands/core/logger.py, using an untrusted string with the command to execute.  \r\n\r\nThis could allow an attacker to inject an arbitrary command, and enable a Command Injection attack.\n\nThe attacker may be able to inject the executed command via user input, input, which is retrieved by the application in the  method, at line 46 of /openhands/core/logger.py.\n\n","markdown":"The application\u0026#39;s  method calls an OS (shell) command with input, at line 46 of /openhands/core/logger.py, using an untrusted string with the command to execute.  \r\n\r\nThis could allow an attacker to inject an arbitrary command, and enable a Command Injection attack.\n\nThe attacker may be able to inject the executed command via user input, input, which is retrieved by the application in the  method, at line 46 of /openhands/core/logger.py.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"The application\u0026#39;s  method calls an OS (shell) command with input, at line 46 of /openhands/core/logger.py, using an untrusted string with the command to execute.  \r\n\r\nThis could allow an attacker to inject an arbitrary command, and enable a Command Injection attack.\n\nThe attacker may be able to inject the executed command via user input, input, which is retrieved by the application in the  method, at line 46 of /openhands/core/logger.py.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"9.0","name":"Command Injection","id":"Command Injection - 10979096389566260942 (sast)","description":"The application\u0026#39;s  method calls an OS (shell) command with input, at line 46 of /openhands/core/logger.py, using an untrusted string with the command to execute.  \r\n\r\nThis could allow an attacker to inject an arbitrary command, and enable a Command Injection attack.\n\nThe attacker may be able to inject the executed command via user input, input, which is retrieved by the application in the  method, at line 46 of /openhands/core/logger.py.\n\n","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"Generic-Api-Key - 01ab7659-d25a-4a1c-9f98-dee9d0cf2e70 (sscs-secret-detection)","name":"Generic-Api-Key","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Remove api-key conv*** from source control and store it in your organization’s secret manager (e.g., AWS Secrets Manager, Azure Key Vault, HashiCorp Vault).","markdown":"Remove api-key conv*** from source control and store it in your organization’s secret manager (e.g., AWS Secrets Manager, Azure Key Vault, HashiCorp Vault)."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Detected a Generic API Key, potentially exposing access to various services and sensitive operations."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Generic-Api-Key","id":"Generic-Api-Key - 01ab7659-d25a-4a1c-9f98-dee9d0cf2e70 (sscs-secret-detection)","description":"Detected a Generic API Key, potentially exposing access to various services and sensitive operations.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sscs-secret-detection"]}},{"id":"Volume Has Sensitive Host Directory - 1c1325ff-831d-43a1-973e-839ae57dfcc0 [Taken from query_id] (kics)","name":"Volume Has Sensitive Host Directory","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Container has sensitive host directory mounted as a volume Value: There is a sensitive directory (/var/run/docker.sock) mounted as a volume Excepted value: There shouldn't be sensitive directory mounted as a volume","markdown":"Container has sensitive host directory mounted as a volume \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eValue:\u003c/strong\u003e There is a sensitive directory (/var/run/docker.sock) mounted as a volume \u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExcepted value:\u003c/strong\u003e There shouldn't be sensitive directory mounted as a volume"},"fullDescription":{"text":"Container has sensitive host directory mounted as a volume Value: There is a sensitive directory (/var/run/docker.sock) mounted as a volume Excepted value: There shouldn't be sensitive directory mounted as a volume"},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Volume Has Sensitive Host Directory","id":"Volume Has Sensitive Host Directory - 1c1325ff-831d-43a1-973e-839ae57dfcc0 [Taken from query_id] (kics)","description":"Container has sensitive host directory mounted as a volume Value: There is a sensitive directory (/var/run/docker.sock) mounted as a volume Excepted value: There shouldn't be sensitive directory mounted as a volume","tags":["security","checkmarx","kics"]}},{"id":"CVE-2022-41409 (containers)","name":"Cve202241409","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Integer overflow vulnerability in pcre2test before 10.41 allows attackers to cause a denial of service or other unspecified impacts via negative input.","markdown":"Integer overflow vulnerability in pcre2test before 10.41 allows attackers to cause a denial of service or other unspecified impacts via negative input."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Integer overflow vulnerability in pcre2test before 10.41 allows attackers to cause a denial of service or other unspecified impacts via negative input."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202241409","id":"CVE-2022-41409 (containers)","description":"Integer overflow vulnerability in pcre2test before 10.41 allows attackers to cause a denial of service or other unspecified impacts via negative input.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2023-31486 (containers)","name":"Cve202331486","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"HTTP::Tiny prior to 0.083, a Perl core module since 5.13.9 and available standalone on CPAN, has an insecure default TLS configuration where users must opt-in to verify certificates.","markdown":"HTTP::Tiny prior to 0.083, a Perl core module since 5.13.9 and available standalone on CPAN, has an insecure default TLS configuration where users must opt-in to verify certificates."},"fullDescription":{"text":"HTTP::Tiny prior to 0.083, a Perl core module since 5.13.9 and available standalone on CPAN, has an insecure default TLS configuration where users must opt-in to verify certificates."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202331486","id":"CVE-2023-31486 (containers)","description":"HTTP::Tiny prior to 0.083, a Perl core module since 5.13.9 and available standalone on CPAN, has an insecure default TLS configuration where users must opt-in to verify certificates.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2026-33671 (sca)","name":"Cve202633671","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"`picomatch` is vulnerable to Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) when processing crafted extglob patterns. Certain patterns using extglob quantifiers such as `+()` and `*()`, especially when combined with overlapping alternatives or nested extglobs, are compiled into regular expressions that can exhibit catastrophic backtracking on non-matching input.","markdown":"`picomatch` is vulnerable to Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) when processing crafted extglob patterns. Certain patterns using extglob quantifiers such as `+()` and `*()`, especially when combined with overlapping alternatives or nested extglobs, are compiled into regular expressions that can exhibit catastrophic backtracking on non-matching input."},"fullDescription":{"text":"`picomatch` is vulnerable to Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) when processing crafted extglob patterns. Certain patterns using extglob quantifiers such as `+()` and `*()`, especially when combined with overlapping alternatives or nested extglobs, are compiled into regular expressions that can exhibit catastrophic backtracking on non-matching input."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202633671","id":"CVE-2026-33671 (sca)","description":"`picomatch` is vulnerable to Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) when processing crafted extglob patterns. Certain patterns using extglob quantifiers such as `+()` and `*()`, especially when combined with overlapping alternatives or nested extglobs, are compiled into regular expressions that can exhibit catastrophic backtracking on non-matching input.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"Last User Is 'root' - 67fd0c4a-68cf-46d7-8c41-bc9fba7e40ae [Taken from query_id] (kics)","name":"Last User Is 'root'","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Leaving the last user as root can cause security risks. Change to another user after running the commands that need privileges Value: Last User is root Excepted value: Last User shouldn't be root","markdown":"Leaving the last user as root can cause security risks. Change to another user after running the commands that need privileges \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eValue:\u003c/strong\u003e Last User is root \u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExcepted value:\u003c/strong\u003e Last User shouldn't be root"},"fullDescription":{"text":"Leaving the last user as root can cause security risks. Change to another user after running the commands that need privileges Value: Last User is root Excepted value: Last User shouldn't be root"},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Last User Is 'root'","id":"Last User Is 'root' - 67fd0c4a-68cf-46d7-8c41-bc9fba7e40ae [Taken from query_id] (kics)","description":"Leaving the last user as root can cause security risks. Change to another user after running the commands that need privileges Value: Last User is root Excepted value: Last User shouldn't be root","tags":["security","checkmarx","kics"]}},{"id":"CVE-2016-20013 (containers)","name":"Cve201620013","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"sha256crypt and sha512crypt through 0.6 allow attackers to cause a denial of service (CPU consumption) because the algorithm\u0026#39;s runtime is proportional to the square of the length of the password.","markdown":"sha256crypt and sha512crypt through 0.6 allow attackers to cause a denial of service (CPU consumption) because the algorithm\u0026#39;s runtime is proportional to the square of the length of the password."},"fullDescription":{"text":"sha256crypt and sha512crypt through 0.6 allow attackers to cause a denial of service (CPU consumption) because the algorithm\u0026#39;s runtime is proportional to the square of the length of the password."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve201620013","id":"CVE-2016-20013 (containers)","description":"sha256crypt and sha512crypt through 0.6 allow attackers to cause a denial of service (CPU consumption) because the algorithm\u0026#39;s runtime is proportional to the square of the length of the password.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2023-47039 (containers)","name":"Cve202347039","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"A vulnerability was found in Perl. This security issue occurs while Perl for Windows relies on the system path environment variable to find the shell (`cmd.exe`). When running an executable that uses the Windows Perl interpreter, Perl attempts to find and execute `cmd.exe` within the operating system. However, due to path search order issues, Perl initially looks for cmd.exe in the current working directory. This flaw allows an attacker with limited privileges to place`cmd.exe` in locations with weak permissions, such as `C:\\ProgramData`. By doing so, arbitrary code can be executed when an administrator attempts to use this executable from these compromised locations.","markdown":"A vulnerability was found in Perl. This security issue occurs while Perl for Windows relies on the system path environment variable to find the shell (`cmd.exe`). When running an executable that uses the Windows Perl interpreter, Perl attempts to find and execute `cmd.exe` within the operating system. However, due to path search order issues, Perl initially looks for cmd.exe in the current working directory. This flaw allows an attacker with limited privileges to place`cmd.exe` in locations with weak permissions, such as `C:\\ProgramData`. By doing so, arbitrary code can be executed when an administrator attempts to use this executable from these compromised locations."},"fullDescription":{"text":"A vulnerability was found in Perl. This security issue occurs while Perl for Windows relies on the system path environment variable to find the shell (`cmd.exe`). When running an executable that uses the Windows Perl interpreter, Perl attempts to find and execute `cmd.exe` within the operating system. However, due to path search order issues, Perl initially looks for cmd.exe in the current working directory. This flaw allows an attacker with limited privileges to place`cmd.exe` in locations with weak permissions, such as `C:\\ProgramData`. By doing so, arbitrary code can be executed when an administrator attempts to use this executable from these compromised locations."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202347039","id":"CVE-2023-47039 (containers)","description":"A vulnerability was found in Perl. This security issue occurs while Perl for Windows relies on the system path environment variable to find the shell (`cmd.exe`). When running an executable that uses the Windows Perl interpreter, Perl attempts to find and execute `cmd.exe` within the operating system. However, due to path search order issues, Perl initially looks for cmd.exe in the current working directory. This flaw allows an attacker with limited privileges to place`cmd.exe` in locations with weak permissions, such as `C:\\ProgramData`. By doing so, arbitrary code can be executed when an administrator attempts to use this executable from these compromised locations.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2026-33671 (containers)","name":"Cve202633671","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"`picomatch` is vulnerable to Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) when processing crafted extglob patterns. Certain patterns using extglob quantifiers such as `+()` and `*()`, especially when combined with overlapping alternatives or nested extglobs, are compiled into regular expressions that can exhibit catastrophic backtracking on non-matching input.","markdown":"`picomatch` is vulnerable to Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) when processing crafted extglob patterns. Certain patterns using extglob quantifiers such as `+()` and `*()`, especially when combined with overlapping alternatives or nested extglobs, are compiled into regular expressions that can exhibit catastrophic backtracking on non-matching input."},"fullDescription":{"text":"`picomatch` is vulnerable to Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) when processing crafted extglob patterns. Certain patterns using extglob quantifiers such as `+()` and `*()`, especially when combined with overlapping alternatives or nested extglobs, are compiled into regular expressions that can exhibit catastrophic backtracking on non-matching input."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202633671","id":"CVE-2026-33671 (containers)","description":"`picomatch` is vulnerable to Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) when processing crafted extglob patterns. Certain patterns using extglob quantifiers such as `+()` and `*()`, especially when combined with overlapping alternatives or nested extglobs, are compiled into regular expressions that can exhibit catastrophic backtracking on non-matching input.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2017-18018 (containers)","name":"Cve201718018","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"In GNU Coreutils through 8.29, chown-core.c in chown and chgrp does not prevent replacement of a plain file with a symlink during use of the POSIX \u0026#34;-R -L\u0026#34; options, which allows local users to modify the ownership of arbitrary files by leveraging a race condition.","markdown":"In GNU Coreutils through 8.29, chown-core.c in chown and chgrp does not prevent replacement of a plain file with a symlink during use of the POSIX \u0026#34;-R -L\u0026#34; options, which allows local users to modify the ownership of arbitrary files by leveraging a race condition."},"fullDescription":{"text":"In GNU Coreutils through 8.29, chown-core.c in chown and chgrp does not prevent replacement of a plain file with a symlink during use of the POSIX \u0026#34;-R -L\u0026#34; options, which allows local users to modify the ownership of arbitrary files by leveraging a race condition."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve201718018","id":"CVE-2017-18018 (containers)","description":"In GNU Coreutils through 8.29, chown-core.c in chown and chgrp does not prevent replacement of a plain file with a symlink during use of the POSIX \u0026#34;-R -L\u0026#34; options, which allows local users to modify the ownership of arbitrary files by leveraging a race condition.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2018-20796 (containers)","name":"Cve201820796","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"In the GNU C Library (aka glibc or libc6) through 2.29, check_dst_limits_calc_pos_1 in posix/regexec.c has Uncontrolled Recursion, as demonstrated by \u0026#39;(\\227|)(\\\\1\\\\1|t1|\\\\\\2537)+\u0026#39; in grep.","markdown":"In the GNU C Library (aka glibc or libc6) through 2.29, check_dst_limits_calc_pos_1 in posix/regexec.c has Uncontrolled Recursion, as demonstrated by \u0026#39;(\\227|)(\\\\1\\\\1|t1|\\\\\\2537)+\u0026#39; in grep."},"fullDescription":{"text":"In the GNU C Library (aka glibc or libc6) through 2.29, check_dst_limits_calc_pos_1 in posix/regexec.c has Uncontrolled Recursion, as demonstrated by \u0026#39;(\\227|)(\\\\1\\\\1|t1|\\\\\\2537)+\u0026#39; in grep."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve201820796","id":"CVE-2018-20796 (containers)","description":"In the GNU C Library (aka glibc or libc6) through 2.29, check_dst_limits_calc_pos_1 in posix/regexec.c has Uncontrolled Recursion, as demonstrated by \u0026#39;(\\227|)(\\\\1\\\\1|t1|\\\\\\2537)+\u0026#39; in grep.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2019-9192 (containers)","name":"Cve20199192","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"In the GNU C Library (aka glibc or libc6) through 2.29, check_dst_limits_calc_pos_1 in posix/regexec.c has Uncontrolled Recursion, as demonstrated by \u0026#39;(|)(\\\\1\\\\1)*\u0026#39; in grep, a different issue than CVE-2018-20796. NOTE: the software maintainer disputes that this is a vulnerability because the behavior occurs only with a crafted pattern","markdown":"In the GNU C Library (aka glibc or libc6) through 2.29, check_dst_limits_calc_pos_1 in posix/regexec.c has Uncontrolled Recursion, as demonstrated by \u0026#39;(|)(\\\\1\\\\1)*\u0026#39; in grep, a different issue than CVE-2018-20796. NOTE: the software maintainer disputes that this is a vulnerability because the behavior occurs only with a crafted pattern"},"fullDescription":{"text":"In the GNU C Library (aka glibc or libc6) through 2.29, check_dst_limits_calc_pos_1 in posix/regexec.c has Uncontrolled Recursion, as demonstrated by \u0026#39;(|)(\\\\1\\\\1)*\u0026#39; in grep, a different issue than CVE-2018-20796. NOTE: the software maintainer disputes that this is a vulnerability because the behavior occurs only with a crafted pattern"},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve20199192","id":"CVE-2019-9192 (containers)","description":"In the GNU C Library (aka glibc or libc6) through 2.29, check_dst_limits_calc_pos_1 in posix/regexec.c has Uncontrolled Recursion, as demonstrated by \u0026#39;(|)(\\\\1\\\\1)*\u0026#39; in grep, a different issue than CVE-2018-20796. NOTE: the software maintainer disputes that this is a vulnerability because the behavior occurs only with a crafted pattern","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2026-4437 (containers)","name":"Cve20264437","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Calling gethostbyaddr or gethostbyaddr_r with a configured nsswitch.conf that specifies the library\u0026#39;s DNS backend in the GNU C Library version 2.34 to version 2.43 could, with a crafted response from the configured DNS server, result in a violation of the DNS specification that causes the application to treat a non-answer section of the DNS response as a valid answer.","markdown":"Calling gethostbyaddr or gethostbyaddr_r with a configured nsswitch.conf that specifies the library\u0026#39;s DNS backend in the GNU C Library version 2.34 to version 2.43 could, with a crafted response from the configured DNS server, result in a violation of the DNS specification that causes the application to treat a non-answer section of the DNS response as a valid answer."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Calling gethostbyaddr or gethostbyaddr_r with a configured nsswitch.conf that specifies the library\u0026#39;s DNS backend in the GNU C Library version 2.34 to version 2.43 could, with a crafted response from the configured DNS server, result in a violation of the DNS specification that causes the application to treat a non-answer section of the DNS response as a valid answer."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve20264437","id":"CVE-2026-4437 (containers)","description":"Calling gethostbyaddr or gethostbyaddr_r with a configured nsswitch.conf that specifies the library\u0026#39;s DNS backend in the GNU C Library version 2.34 to version 2.43 could, with a crafted response from the configured DNS server, result in a violation of the DNS specification that causes the application to treat a non-answer section of the DNS response as a valid answer.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2026-2673 (containers)","name":"Cve20262673","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Issue summary: An OpenSSL TLS 1.3 server may fail to negotiate the expected\npreferred key exchange group when its key exchange group configuration includes\nthe default by using the \u0026#39;DEFAULT\u0026#39; keyword.\n\nImpact summary: A less preferred key exchange may be used even when a more\npreferred group is supported by both client and server, if the group\nwas not included among the client\u0026#39;s initial predicated keyshares.\nThis will sometimes be the case with the new hybrid post-quantum groups,\nif the client chooses to defer their use until specifically requested by\nthe server.\n\nIf an OpenSSL TLS 1.3 server\u0026#39;s configuration uses the \u0026#39;DEFAULT\u0026#39; keyword to\ninterpolate the built-in default group list into its own configuration, perhaps\nadding or removing specific elements, then an implementation defect causes the\n\u0026#39;DEFAULT\u0026#39; list to lose its \u0026#39;tuple\u0026#39; structure, and all server-supported groups\nwere treated as a single sufficiently secure \u0026#39;tuple\u0026#39;, with the server not\nsending a Hello Retry Request (HRR) even when a group in a more preferred tuple\nwas mutually supported.\n\nAs a result, the client and server might fail to negotiate a mutually supported\npost-quantum key agreement group, such as \u0026#39;X25519MLKEM768\u0026#39;, if the client\u0026#39;s\nconfiguration results in only \u0026#39;classical\u0026#39; groups (such as \u0026#39;X25519\u0026#39; being the\nonly ones in the client\u0026#39;s initial keyshare prediction).\n\nOpenSSL 3.5 and later support a new syntax for selecting the most preferred TLS\n1.3 key agreement group on TLS servers.  The old syntax had a single \u0026#39;flat\u0026#39;\nlist of groups, and treated all the supported groups as sufficiently secure.\nIf any of the keyshares predicted by the client were supported by the server\nthe most preferred among these was selected, even if other groups supported by\nthe client, but not included in the list of predicted keyshares would have been\nmore preferred, if included.\n\nThe new syntax partitions the groups into distinct \u0026#39;tuples\u0026#39; of roughly\nequivalent security.  Within each tuple the most preferred group included among\nthe client\u0026#39;s predicted keyshares is chosen, but if the client supports a group\nfrom a more preferred tuple, but did not predict any corresponding keyshares,\nthe server will ask the client to retry the ClientHello (by issuing a Hello\nRetry Request or HRR) with the most preferred mutually supported group.\n\nThe above works as expected when the server\u0026#39;s configuration uses the built-in\ndefault group list, or explicitly defines its own list by directly defining the\nvarious desired groups and group \u0026#39;tuples\u0026#39;.\n\nNo OpenSSL FIPS modules are affected by this issue, the code in question lies\noutside the FIPS boundary.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6 and 3.5 are vulnerable to this issue.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.6.2 once it is released.\nOpenSSL 3.5 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.5.6 once it is released.\n\nOpenSSL 3.4, 3.3, 3.0, 1.0.2 and 1.1.1 are not affected by this issue.","markdown":"Issue summary: An OpenSSL TLS 1.3 server may fail to negotiate the expected\npreferred key exchange group when its key exchange group configuration includes\nthe default by using the \u0026#39;DEFAULT\u0026#39; keyword.\n\nImpact summary: A less preferred key exchange may be used even when a more\npreferred group is supported by both client and server, if the group\nwas not included among the client\u0026#39;s initial predicated keyshares.\nThis will sometimes be the case with the new hybrid post-quantum groups,\nif the client chooses to defer their use until specifically requested by\nthe server.\n\nIf an OpenSSL TLS 1.3 server\u0026#39;s configuration uses the \u0026#39;DEFAULT\u0026#39; keyword to\ninterpolate the built-in default group list into its own configuration, perhaps\nadding or removing specific elements, then an implementation defect causes the\n\u0026#39;DEFAULT\u0026#39; list to lose its \u0026#39;tuple\u0026#39; structure, and all server-supported groups\nwere treated as a single sufficiently secure \u0026#39;tuple\u0026#39;, with the server not\nsending a Hello Retry Request (HRR) even when a group in a more preferred tuple\nwas mutually supported.\n\nAs a result, the client and server might fail to negotiate a mutually supported\npost-quantum key agreement group, such as \u0026#39;X25519MLKEM768\u0026#39;, if the client\u0026#39;s\nconfiguration results in only \u0026#39;classical\u0026#39; groups (such as \u0026#39;X25519\u0026#39; being the\nonly ones in the client\u0026#39;s initial keyshare prediction).\n\nOpenSSL 3.5 and later support a new syntax for selecting the most preferred TLS\n1.3 key agreement group on TLS servers.  The old syntax had a single \u0026#39;flat\u0026#39;\nlist of groups, and treated all the supported groups as sufficiently secure.\nIf any of the keyshares predicted by the client were supported by the server\nthe most preferred among these was selected, even if other groups supported by\nthe client, but not included in the list of predicted keyshares would have been\nmore preferred, if included.\n\nThe new syntax partitions the groups into distinct \u0026#39;tuples\u0026#39; of roughly\nequivalent security.  Within each tuple the most preferred group included among\nthe client\u0026#39;s predicted keyshares is chosen, but if the client supports a group\nfrom a more preferred tuple, but did not predict any corresponding keyshares,\nthe server will ask the client to retry the ClientHello (by issuing a Hello\nRetry Request or HRR) with the most preferred mutually supported group.\n\nThe above works as expected when the server\u0026#39;s configuration uses the built-in\ndefault group list, or explicitly defines its own list by directly defining the\nvarious desired groups and group \u0026#39;tuples\u0026#39;.\n\nNo OpenSSL FIPS modules are affected by this issue, the code in question lies\noutside the FIPS boundary.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6 and 3.5 are vulnerable to this issue.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.6.2 once it is released.\nOpenSSL 3.5 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.5.6 once it is released.\n\nOpenSSL 3.4, 3.3, 3.0, 1.0.2 and 1.1.1 are not affected by this issue."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Issue summary: An OpenSSL TLS 1.3 server may fail to negotiate the expected\npreferred key exchange group when its key exchange group configuration includes\nthe default by using the \u0026#39;DEFAULT\u0026#39; keyword.\n\nImpact summary: A less preferred key exchange may be used even when a more\npreferred group is supported by both client and server, if the group\nwas not included among the client\u0026#39;s initial predicated keyshares.\nThis will sometimes be the case with the new hybrid post-quantum groups,\nif the client chooses to defer their use until specifically requested by\nthe server.\n\nIf an OpenSSL TLS 1.3 server\u0026#39;s configuration uses the \u0026#39;DEFAULT\u0026#39; keyword to\ninterpolate the built-in default group list into its own configuration, perhaps\nadding or removing specific elements, then an implementation defect causes the\n\u0026#39;DEFAULT\u0026#39; list to lose its \u0026#39;tuple\u0026#39; structure, and all server-supported groups\nwere treated as a single sufficiently secure \u0026#39;tuple\u0026#39;, with the server not\nsending a Hello Retry Request (HRR) even when a group in a more preferred tuple\nwas mutually supported.\n\nAs a result, the client and server might fail to negotiate a mutually supported\npost-quantum key agreement group, such as \u0026#39;X25519MLKEM768\u0026#39;, if the client\u0026#39;s\nconfiguration results in only \u0026#39;classical\u0026#39; groups (such as \u0026#39;X25519\u0026#39; being the\nonly ones in the client\u0026#39;s initial keyshare prediction).\n\nOpenSSL 3.5 and later support a new syntax for selecting the most preferred TLS\n1.3 key agreement group on TLS servers.  The old syntax had a single \u0026#39;flat\u0026#39;\nlist of groups, and treated all the supported groups as sufficiently secure.\nIf any of the keyshares predicted by the client were supported by the server\nthe most preferred among these was selected, even if other groups supported by\nthe client, but not included in the list of predicted keyshares would have been\nmore preferred, if included.\n\nThe new syntax partitions the groups into distinct \u0026#39;tuples\u0026#39; of roughly\nequivalent security.  Within each tuple the most preferred group included among\nthe client\u0026#39;s predicted keyshares is chosen, but if the client supports a group\nfrom a more preferred tuple, but did not predict any corresponding keyshares,\nthe server will ask the client to retry the ClientHello (by issuing a Hello\nRetry Request or HRR) with the most preferred mutually supported group.\n\nThe above works as expected when the server\u0026#39;s configuration uses the built-in\ndefault group list, or explicitly defines its own list by directly defining the\nvarious desired groups and group \u0026#39;tuples\u0026#39;.\n\nNo OpenSSL FIPS modules are affected by this issue, the code in question lies\noutside the FIPS boundary.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6 and 3.5 are vulnerable to this issue.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.6.2 once it is released.\nOpenSSL 3.5 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.5.6 once it is released.\n\nOpenSSL 3.4, 3.3, 3.0, 1.0.2 and 1.1.1 are not affected by this issue."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve20262673","id":"CVE-2026-2673 (containers)","description":"Issue summary: An OpenSSL TLS 1.3 server may fail to negotiate the expected\npreferred key exchange group when its key exchange group configuration includes\nthe default by using the \u0026#39;DEFAULT\u0026#39; keyword.\n\nImpact summary: A less preferred key exchange may be used even when a more\npreferred group is supported by both client and server, if the group\nwas not included among the client\u0026#39;s initial predicated keyshares.\nThis will sometimes be the case with the new hybrid post-quantum groups,\nif the client chooses to defer their use until specifically requested by\nthe server.\n\nIf an OpenSSL TLS 1.3 server\u0026#39;s configuration uses the \u0026#39;DEFAULT\u0026#39; keyword to\ninterpolate the built-in default group list into its own configuration, perhaps\nadding or removing specific elements, then an implementation defect causes the\n\u0026#39;DEFAULT\u0026#39; list to lose its \u0026#39;tuple\u0026#39; structure, and all server-supported groups\nwere treated as a single sufficiently secure \u0026#39;tuple\u0026#39;, with the server not\nsending a Hello Retry Request (HRR) even when a group in a more preferred tuple\nwas mutually supported.\n\nAs a result, the client and server might fail to negotiate a mutually supported\npost-quantum key agreement group, such as \u0026#39;X25519MLKEM768\u0026#39;, if the client\u0026#39;s\nconfiguration results in only \u0026#39;classical\u0026#39; groups (such as \u0026#39;X25519\u0026#39; being the\nonly ones in the client\u0026#39;s initial keyshare prediction).\n\nOpenSSL 3.5 and later support a new syntax for selecting the most preferred TLS\n1.3 key agreement group on TLS servers.  The old syntax had a single \u0026#39;flat\u0026#39;\nlist of groups, and treated all the supported groups as sufficiently secure.\nIf any of the keyshares predicted by the client were supported by the server\nthe most preferred among these was selected, even if other groups supported by\nthe client, but not included in the list of predicted keyshares would have been\nmore preferred, if included.\n\nThe new syntax partitions the groups into distinct \u0026#39;tuples\u0026#39; of roughly\nequivalent security.  Within each tuple the most preferred group included among\nthe client\u0026#39;s predicted keyshares is chosen, but if the client supports a group\nfrom a more preferred tuple, but did not predict any corresponding keyshares,\nthe server will ask the client to retry the ClientHello (by issuing a Hello\nRetry Request or HRR) with the most preferred mutually supported group.\n\nThe above works as expected when the server\u0026#39;s configuration uses the built-in\ndefault group list, or explicitly defines its own list by directly defining the\nvarious desired groups and group \u0026#39;tuples\u0026#39;.\n\nNo OpenSSL FIPS modules are affected by this issue, the code in question lies\noutside the FIPS boundary.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6 and 3.5 are vulnerable to this issue.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.6.2 once it is released.\nOpenSSL 3.5 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.5.6 once it is released.\n\nOpenSSL 3.4, 3.3, 3.0, 1.0.2 and 1.1.1 are not affected by this issue.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-70873 (containers)","name":"Cve202570873","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"An information disclosure issue in the zipfileInflate function in the zipfile extension in SQLite v3.51.1 and earlier allows attackers to obtain heap memory via supplying a crafted ZIP file.","markdown":"An information disclosure issue in the zipfileInflate function in the zipfile extension in SQLite v3.51.1 and earlier allows attackers to obtain heap memory via supplying a crafted ZIP file."},"fullDescription":{"text":"An information disclosure issue in the zipfileInflate function in the zipfile extension in SQLite v3.51.1 and earlier allows attackers to obtain heap memory via supplying a crafted ZIP file."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202570873","id":"CVE-2025-70873 (containers)","description":"An information disclosure issue in the zipfileInflate function in the zipfile extension in SQLite v3.51.1 and earlier allows attackers to obtain heap memory via supplying a crafted ZIP file.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2026-2219 (containers)","name":"Cve20262219","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"It was discovered that dpkg-deb (a component of dpkg, the Debian package management system) does not properly validate the end of the data stream when uncompressing a zstd-compressed .deb archive, which may result in denial of service (infinite loop spinning the CPU).","markdown":"It was discovered that dpkg-deb (a component of dpkg, the Debian package management system) does not properly validate the end of the data stream when uncompressing a zstd-compressed .deb archive, which may result in denial of service (infinite loop spinning the CPU)."},"fullDescription":{"text":"It was discovered that dpkg-deb (a component of dpkg, the Debian package management system) does not properly validate the end of the data stream when uncompressing a zstd-compressed .deb archive, which may result in denial of service (infinite loop spinning the CPU)."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve20262219","id":"CVE-2026-2219 (containers)","description":"It was discovered that dpkg-deb (a component of dpkg, the Debian package management system) does not properly validate the end of the data stream when uncompressing a zstd-compressed .deb archive, which may result in denial of service (infinite loop spinning the CPU).","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-15281 (containers)","name":"Cve202515281","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Calling wordexp with \u0026#34;WRDE_REUSE\u0026#34; in conjunction with \u0026#34;WRDE_APPEND\u0026#34; in the GNU C Library version 2.0 through 2.42 may cause the interface to return uninitialized memory in the we_wordv member, which on subsequent calls to wordfree may abort the process.","markdown":"Calling wordexp with \u0026#34;WRDE_REUSE\u0026#34; in conjunction with \u0026#34;WRDE_APPEND\u0026#34; in the GNU C Library version 2.0 through 2.42 may cause the interface to return uninitialized memory in the we_wordv member, which on subsequent calls to wordfree may abort the process."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Calling wordexp with \u0026#34;WRDE_REUSE\u0026#34; in conjunction with \u0026#34;WRDE_APPEND\u0026#34; in the GNU C Library version 2.0 through 2.42 may cause the interface to return uninitialized memory in the we_wordv member, which on subsequent calls to wordfree may abort the process."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202515281","id":"CVE-2025-15281 (containers)","description":"Calling wordexp with \u0026#34;WRDE_REUSE\u0026#34; in conjunction with \u0026#34;WRDE_APPEND\u0026#34; in the GNU C Library version 2.0 through 2.42 may cause the interface to return uninitialized memory in the we_wordv member, which on subsequent calls to wordfree may abort the process.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2026-0861 (containers)","name":"Cve20260861","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Passing too large an alignment to the memalign suite of functions (memalign, posix_memalign, aligned_alloc, valloc, pvalloc) in the GNU C Library versions from 2.30 through 2.42 may result in an Integer Overflow, which could consequently result in a heap corruption.","markdown":"Passing too large an alignment to the memalign suite of functions (memalign, posix_memalign, aligned_alloc, valloc, pvalloc) in the GNU C Library versions from 2.30 through 2.42 may result in an Integer Overflow, which could consequently result in a heap corruption."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Passing too large an alignment to the memalign suite of functions (memalign, posix_memalign, aligned_alloc, valloc, pvalloc) in the GNU C Library versions from 2.30 through 2.42 may result in an Integer Overflow, which could consequently result in a heap corruption."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve20260861","id":"CVE-2026-0861 (containers)","description":"Passing too large an alignment to the memalign suite of functions (memalign, posix_memalign, aligned_alloc, valloc, pvalloc) in the GNU C Library versions from 2.30 through 2.42 may result in an Integer Overflow, which could consequently result in a heap corruption.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-15467 (containers)","name":"Cve202515467","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Issue summary: Parsing CMS AuthEnvelopedData message with maliciously crafted AEAD parameters can trigger a stack buffer overflow.\nImpact summary: A stack buffer overflow may lead to a crash, causing Denial-of-Service (DoS), or potentially remote code execution.\n\nWhen parsing CMS \u0026#34;AuthEnvelopedData\u0026#34; structures that use AEAD ciphers such as AES-GCM, the IV (Initialization Vector) encoded in the ASN.1 parameters is copied into a fixed-size stack buffer without verifying that its length fits\nthe destination. An attacker can supply a crafted CMS message with an oversized IV, causing a stack-based out-of-bounds write before any authentication or tag verification occurs.\n\nApplications and services that parse untrusted CMS or PKCS#7 content using\nAEAD ciphers (e.g., S/MIME AuthEnvelopedData with AES-GCM) are vulnerable.\\Because the overflow occurs prior to authentication, no valid key material is required to trigger it. While exploitability to remote code execution depends on platform and toolchain mitigations, the stack-based write primitive represents a severe risk.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the CMS implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are vulnerable to this issue.\n\nOpenSSL 1.1.1 and 1.0.2 are not affected by this issue.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.6.1.\n\nOpenSSL 3.5 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.5.5.\n\nOpenSSL 3.4 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.4.4.\n\nOpenSSL 3.3 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.3.6.\n\nOpenSSL 3.0 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.0.19","markdown":"Issue summary: Parsing CMS AuthEnvelopedData message with maliciously crafted AEAD parameters can trigger a stack buffer overflow.\nImpact summary: A stack buffer overflow may lead to a crash, causing Denial-of-Service (DoS), or potentially remote code execution.\n\nWhen parsing CMS \u0026#34;AuthEnvelopedData\u0026#34; structures that use AEAD ciphers such as AES-GCM, the IV (Initialization Vector) encoded in the ASN.1 parameters is copied into a fixed-size stack buffer without verifying that its length fits\nthe destination. An attacker can supply a crafted CMS message with an oversized IV, causing a stack-based out-of-bounds write before any authentication or tag verification occurs.\n\nApplications and services that parse untrusted CMS or PKCS#7 content using\nAEAD ciphers (e.g., S/MIME AuthEnvelopedData with AES-GCM) are vulnerable.\\Because the overflow occurs prior to authentication, no valid key material is required to trigger it. While exploitability to remote code execution depends on platform and toolchain mitigations, the stack-based write primitive represents a severe risk.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the CMS implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are vulnerable to this issue.\n\nOpenSSL 1.1.1 and 1.0.2 are not affected by this issue.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.6.1.\n\nOpenSSL 3.5 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.5.5.\n\nOpenSSL 3.4 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.4.4.\n\nOpenSSL 3.3 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.3.6.\n\nOpenSSL 3.0 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.0.19"},"fullDescription":{"text":"Issue summary: Parsing CMS AuthEnvelopedData message with maliciously crafted AEAD parameters can trigger a stack buffer overflow.\nImpact summary: A stack buffer overflow may lead to a crash, causing Denial-of-Service (DoS), or potentially remote code execution.\n\nWhen parsing CMS \u0026#34;AuthEnvelopedData\u0026#34; structures that use AEAD ciphers such as AES-GCM, the IV (Initialization Vector) encoded in the ASN.1 parameters is copied into a fixed-size stack buffer without verifying that its length fits\nthe destination. An attacker can supply a crafted CMS message with an oversized IV, causing a stack-based out-of-bounds write before any authentication or tag verification occurs.\n\nApplications and services that parse untrusted CMS or PKCS#7 content using\nAEAD ciphers (e.g., S/MIME AuthEnvelopedData with AES-GCM) are vulnerable.\\Because the overflow occurs prior to authentication, no valid key material is required to trigger it. While exploitability to remote code execution depends on platform and toolchain mitigations, the stack-based write primitive represents a severe risk.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the CMS implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are vulnerable to this issue.\n\nOpenSSL 1.1.1 and 1.0.2 are not affected by this issue.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.6.1.\n\nOpenSSL 3.5 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.5.5.\n\nOpenSSL 3.4 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.4.4.\n\nOpenSSL 3.3 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.3.6.\n\nOpenSSL 3.0 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.0.19"},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202515467","id":"CVE-2025-15467 (containers)","description":"Issue summary: Parsing CMS AuthEnvelopedData message with maliciously crafted AEAD parameters can trigger a stack buffer overflow.\nImpact summary: A stack buffer overflow may lead to a crash, causing Denial-of-Service (DoS), or potentially remote code execution.\n\nWhen parsing CMS \u0026#34;AuthEnvelopedData\u0026#34; structures that use AEAD ciphers such as AES-GCM, the IV (Initialization Vector) encoded in the ASN.1 parameters is copied into a fixed-size stack buffer without verifying that its length fits\nthe destination. An attacker can supply a crafted CMS message with an oversized IV, causing a stack-based out-of-bounds write before any authentication or tag verification occurs.\n\nApplications and services that parse untrusted CMS or PKCS#7 content using\nAEAD ciphers (e.g., S/MIME AuthEnvelopedData with AES-GCM) are vulnerable.\\Because the overflow occurs prior to authentication, no valid key material is required to trigger it. While exploitability to remote code execution depends on platform and toolchain mitigations, the stack-based write primitive represents a severe risk.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the CMS implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are vulnerable to this issue.\n\nOpenSSL 1.1.1 and 1.0.2 are not affected by this issue.\n\nOpenSSL 3.6 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.6.1.\n\nOpenSSL 3.5 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.5.5.\n\nOpenSSL 3.4 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.4.4.\n\nOpenSSL 3.3 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.3.6.\n\nOpenSSL 3.0 users should upgrade to OpenSSL 3.0.19","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-69419 (containers)","name":"Cve202569419","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Issue summary: Calling \u0026#34;PKCS12_get_friendlyname()\u0026#34; function on a maliciously\ncrafted PKCS#12 file with a BMPString (UTF-16BE) friendly name containing\nnon-ASCII BMP code point can trigger a one byte write before the allocated\nbuffer.\n\nImpact summary: The out-of-bounds write can cause a memory corruption\nwhich can have various consequences including a Denial-of-Service.\n\nThe \u0026#34;OPENSSL_uni2utf8()\u0026#34; function performs a two-pass conversion of a PKCS#12\nBMPString (UTF-16BE) to UTF-8. In the second pass, when emitting UTF-8 bytes,\nthe helper function \u0026#34;bmp_to_utf8()\u0026#34; incorrectly forwards the remaining UTF-16\nsource byte count as the destination buffer capacity to \u0026#34;UTF8_putc()\u0026#34;. For BMP\ncode points above U+07FF, UTF-8 requires three bytes, but the forwarded\ncapacity can be just two bytes. \u0026#34;UTF8_putc()\u0026#34; then returns -1, and this negative\nvalue is added to the output length without validation, causing the\nlength to become negative. The subsequent trailing NUL byte is then written\nat a negative offset, causing write outside of heap allocated buffer.\n\nThe vulnerability is reachable via the public \u0026#34;PKCS12_get_friendlyname()\u0026#34; API\nwhen parsing attacker-controlled PKCS#12 files. While \u0026#34;PKCS12_parse()\u0026#34;uses a\ndifferent code path that avoids this issue, \u0026#34;PKCS12_get_friendlyname()\u0026#34; directly\ninvokes the vulnerable function. Exploitation requires an attacker to provide\na malicious PKCS#12 file to be parsed by the application and the attacker\ncan just trigger a one zero byte write before the allocated buffer.\nFor that reason the issue was assessed as Low severity according to our\nSecurity Policy.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue,\nas the PKCS#12 implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary.\n\n. OpenSSL versions 3.6 prior to 3.6.1, 3.5 prior to 3.5.5, 3.4 prior to 3.4.4, 3.3 prior to 3.3.6, 3.0 prior to 3.0.19 and 1.1.1.x  1.1.1 are vulnerable to this issue. \n\nOpenSSL 1.0.2.x is not affected by this issue.","markdown":"Issue summary: Calling \u0026#34;PKCS12_get_friendlyname()\u0026#34; function on a maliciously\ncrafted PKCS#12 file with a BMPString (UTF-16BE) friendly name containing\nnon-ASCII BMP code point can trigger a one byte write before the allocated\nbuffer.\n\nImpact summary: The out-of-bounds write can cause a memory corruption\nwhich can have various consequences including a Denial-of-Service.\n\nThe \u0026#34;OPENSSL_uni2utf8()\u0026#34; function performs a two-pass conversion of a PKCS#12\nBMPString (UTF-16BE) to UTF-8. In the second pass, when emitting UTF-8 bytes,\nthe helper function \u0026#34;bmp_to_utf8()\u0026#34; incorrectly forwards the remaining UTF-16\nsource byte count as the destination buffer capacity to \u0026#34;UTF8_putc()\u0026#34;. For BMP\ncode points above U+07FF, UTF-8 requires three bytes, but the forwarded\ncapacity can be just two bytes. \u0026#34;UTF8_putc()\u0026#34; then returns -1, and this negative\nvalue is added to the output length without validation, causing the\nlength to become negative. The subsequent trailing NUL byte is then written\nat a negative offset, causing write outside of heap allocated buffer.\n\nThe vulnerability is reachable via the public \u0026#34;PKCS12_get_friendlyname()\u0026#34; API\nwhen parsing attacker-controlled PKCS#12 files. While \u0026#34;PKCS12_parse()\u0026#34;uses a\ndifferent code path that avoids this issue, \u0026#34;PKCS12_get_friendlyname()\u0026#34; directly\ninvokes the vulnerable function. Exploitation requires an attacker to provide\na malicious PKCS#12 file to be parsed by the application and the attacker\ncan just trigger a one zero byte write before the allocated buffer.\nFor that reason the issue was assessed as Low severity according to our\nSecurity Policy.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue,\nas the PKCS#12 implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary.\n\n. OpenSSL versions 3.6 prior to 3.6.1, 3.5 prior to 3.5.5, 3.4 prior to 3.4.4, 3.3 prior to 3.3.6, 3.0 prior to 3.0.19 and 1.1.1.x  1.1.1 are vulnerable to this issue. \n\nOpenSSL 1.0.2.x is not affected by this issue."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Issue summary: Calling \u0026#34;PKCS12_get_friendlyname()\u0026#34; function on a maliciously\ncrafted PKCS#12 file with a BMPString (UTF-16BE) friendly name containing\nnon-ASCII BMP code point can trigger a one byte write before the allocated\nbuffer.\n\nImpact summary: The out-of-bounds write can cause a memory corruption\nwhich can have various consequences including a Denial-of-Service.\n\nThe \u0026#34;OPENSSL_uni2utf8()\u0026#34; function performs a two-pass conversion of a PKCS#12\nBMPString (UTF-16BE) to UTF-8. In the second pass, when emitting UTF-8 bytes,\nthe helper function \u0026#34;bmp_to_utf8()\u0026#34; incorrectly forwards the remaining UTF-16\nsource byte count as the destination buffer capacity to \u0026#34;UTF8_putc()\u0026#34;. For BMP\ncode points above U+07FF, UTF-8 requires three bytes, but the forwarded\ncapacity can be just two bytes. \u0026#34;UTF8_putc()\u0026#34; then returns -1, and this negative\nvalue is added to the output length without validation, causing the\nlength to become negative. The subsequent trailing NUL byte is then written\nat a negative offset, causing write outside of heap allocated buffer.\n\nThe vulnerability is reachable via the public \u0026#34;PKCS12_get_friendlyname()\u0026#34; API\nwhen parsing attacker-controlled PKCS#12 files. While \u0026#34;PKCS12_parse()\u0026#34;uses a\ndifferent code path that avoids this issue, \u0026#34;PKCS12_get_friendlyname()\u0026#34; directly\ninvokes the vulnerable function. Exploitation requires an attacker to provide\na malicious PKCS#12 file to be parsed by the application and the attacker\ncan just trigger a one zero byte write before the allocated buffer.\nFor that reason the issue was assessed as Low severity according to our\nSecurity Policy.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue,\nas the PKCS#12 implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary.\n\n. OpenSSL versions 3.6 prior to 3.6.1, 3.5 prior to 3.5.5, 3.4 prior to 3.4.4, 3.3 prior to 3.3.6, 3.0 prior to 3.0.19 and 1.1.1.x  1.1.1 are vulnerable to this issue. \n\nOpenSSL 1.0.2.x is not affected by this issue."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202569419","id":"CVE-2025-69419 (containers)","description":"Issue summary: Calling \u0026#34;PKCS12_get_friendlyname()\u0026#34; function on a maliciously\ncrafted PKCS#12 file with a BMPString (UTF-16BE) friendly name containing\nnon-ASCII BMP code point can trigger a one byte write before the allocated\nbuffer.\n\nImpact summary: The out-of-bounds write can cause a memory corruption\nwhich can have various consequences including a Denial-of-Service.\n\nThe \u0026#34;OPENSSL_uni2utf8()\u0026#34; function performs a two-pass conversion of a PKCS#12\nBMPString (UTF-16BE) to UTF-8. In the second pass, when emitting UTF-8 bytes,\nthe helper function \u0026#34;bmp_to_utf8()\u0026#34; incorrectly forwards the remaining UTF-16\nsource byte count as the destination buffer capacity to \u0026#34;UTF8_putc()\u0026#34;. For BMP\ncode points above U+07FF, UTF-8 requires three bytes, but the forwarded\ncapacity can be just two bytes. \u0026#34;UTF8_putc()\u0026#34; then returns -1, and this negative\nvalue is added to the output length without validation, causing the\nlength to become negative. The subsequent trailing NUL byte is then written\nat a negative offset, causing write outside of heap allocated buffer.\n\nThe vulnerability is reachable via the public \u0026#34;PKCS12_get_friendlyname()\u0026#34; API\nwhen parsing attacker-controlled PKCS#12 files. While \u0026#34;PKCS12_parse()\u0026#34;uses a\ndifferent code path that avoids this issue, \u0026#34;PKCS12_get_friendlyname()\u0026#34; directly\ninvokes the vulnerable function. Exploitation requires an attacker to provide\na malicious PKCS#12 file to be parsed by the application and the attacker\ncan just trigger a one zero byte write before the allocated buffer.\nFor that reason the issue was assessed as Low severity according to our\nSecurity Policy.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue,\nas the PKCS#12 implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary.\n\n. OpenSSL versions 3.6 prior to 3.6.1, 3.5 prior to 3.5.5, 3.4 prior to 3.4.4, 3.3 prior to 3.3.6, 3.0 prior to 3.0.19 and 1.1.1.x  1.1.1 are vulnerable to this issue. \n\nOpenSSL 1.0.2.x is not affected by this issue.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-69420 (containers)","name":"Cve202569420","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Issue summary: A type confusion vulnerability exists in the TimeStamp Response verification code where an ASN1_TYPE union member is accessed without first\nvalidating the type, causing an invalid or NULL pointer dereference when processing a malformed TimeStamp Response file.\n\nImpact summary: An application calling \u0026#34;TS_RESP_verify_response()\u0026#34; with a malformed TimeStamp Response can be caused to dereference an invalid or\nNULL pointer when reading, resulting in a Denial of Service.\n\nThe functions \u0026#34;ossl_ess_get_signing_cert()\u0026#34; and \u0026#34;ossl_ess_get_signing_cert_v2()\u0026#34; access the signing cert attribute value without validating its type. When the type is not V_ASN1_SEQUENCE, this results in accessing invalid memory through the ASN1_TYPE union, causing a crash.\n\nExploiting this vulnerability requires an attacker to provide a malformed TimeStamp Response to an application that verifies timestamp responses. The\nTimeStamp protocol (RFC 3161) is not widely used and the impact of the exploit is just a Denial of Service. For these reasons the issue was assessed as Low severity.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the TimeStamp Response implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module\nboundary.\n\nOpenSSL versions 3.6 prior to 3.6.1, 3.5 prior to 3.5.5, 3.4 prior to 3.4.4, 3.3 prior to 3.3.6, 3.0 prior to 3.0.19, 1.1.1.x are vulnerable to this issue. OpenSSL 1.0.2 is not affected by this issue.","markdown":"Issue summary: A type confusion vulnerability exists in the TimeStamp Response verification code where an ASN1_TYPE union member is accessed without first\nvalidating the type, causing an invalid or NULL pointer dereference when processing a malformed TimeStamp Response file.\n\nImpact summary: An application calling \u0026#34;TS_RESP_verify_response()\u0026#34; with a malformed TimeStamp Response can be caused to dereference an invalid or\nNULL pointer when reading, resulting in a Denial of Service.\n\nThe functions \u0026#34;ossl_ess_get_signing_cert()\u0026#34; and \u0026#34;ossl_ess_get_signing_cert_v2()\u0026#34; access the signing cert attribute value without validating its type. When the type is not V_ASN1_SEQUENCE, this results in accessing invalid memory through the ASN1_TYPE union, causing a crash.\n\nExploiting this vulnerability requires an attacker to provide a malformed TimeStamp Response to an application that verifies timestamp responses. The\nTimeStamp protocol (RFC 3161) is not widely used and the impact of the exploit is just a Denial of Service. For these reasons the issue was assessed as Low severity.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the TimeStamp Response implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module\nboundary.\n\nOpenSSL versions 3.6 prior to 3.6.1, 3.5 prior to 3.5.5, 3.4 prior to 3.4.4, 3.3 prior to 3.3.6, 3.0 prior to 3.0.19, 1.1.1.x are vulnerable to this issue. OpenSSL 1.0.2 is not affected by this issue."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Issue summary: A type confusion vulnerability exists in the TimeStamp Response verification code where an ASN1_TYPE union member is accessed without first\nvalidating the type, causing an invalid or NULL pointer dereference when processing a malformed TimeStamp Response file.\n\nImpact summary: An application calling \u0026#34;TS_RESP_verify_response()\u0026#34; with a malformed TimeStamp Response can be caused to dereference an invalid or\nNULL pointer when reading, resulting in a Denial of Service.\n\nThe functions \u0026#34;ossl_ess_get_signing_cert()\u0026#34; and \u0026#34;ossl_ess_get_signing_cert_v2()\u0026#34; access the signing cert attribute value without validating its type. When the type is not V_ASN1_SEQUENCE, this results in accessing invalid memory through the ASN1_TYPE union, causing a crash.\n\nExploiting this vulnerability requires an attacker to provide a malformed TimeStamp Response to an application that verifies timestamp responses. The\nTimeStamp protocol (RFC 3161) is not widely used and the impact of the exploit is just a Denial of Service. For these reasons the issue was assessed as Low severity.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the TimeStamp Response implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module\nboundary.\n\nOpenSSL versions 3.6 prior to 3.6.1, 3.5 prior to 3.5.5, 3.4 prior to 3.4.4, 3.3 prior to 3.3.6, 3.0 prior to 3.0.19, 1.1.1.x are vulnerable to this issue. OpenSSL 1.0.2 is not affected by this issue."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202569420","id":"CVE-2025-69420 (containers)","description":"Issue summary: A type confusion vulnerability exists in the TimeStamp Response verification code where an ASN1_TYPE union member is accessed without first\nvalidating the type, causing an invalid or NULL pointer dereference when processing a malformed TimeStamp Response file.\n\nImpact summary: An application calling \u0026#34;TS_RESP_verify_response()\u0026#34; with a malformed TimeStamp Response can be caused to dereference an invalid or\nNULL pointer when reading, resulting in a Denial of Service.\n\nThe functions \u0026#34;ossl_ess_get_signing_cert()\u0026#34; and \u0026#34;ossl_ess_get_signing_cert_v2()\u0026#34; access the signing cert attribute value without validating its type. When the type is not V_ASN1_SEQUENCE, this results in accessing invalid memory through the ASN1_TYPE union, causing a crash.\n\nExploiting this vulnerability requires an attacker to provide a malformed TimeStamp Response to an application that verifies timestamp responses. The\nTimeStamp protocol (RFC 3161) is not widely used and the impact of the exploit is just a Denial of Service. For these reasons the issue was assessed as Low severity.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the TimeStamp Response implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module\nboundary.\n\nOpenSSL versions 3.6 prior to 3.6.1, 3.5 prior to 3.5.5, 3.4 prior to 3.4.4, 3.3 prior to 3.3.6, 3.0 prior to 3.0.19, 1.1.1.x are vulnerable to this issue. OpenSSL 1.0.2 is not affected by this issue.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-69421 (containers)","name":"Cve202569421","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Issue summary: Processing a malformed PKCS#12 file can trigger a NULL Pointer Dereference in the \u0026#34;PKCS12_item_decrypt_d2i_ex()\u0026#34; function.\n\nImpact summary: A NULL pointer dereference can trigger a crash which leads to Denial of Service for an application processing PKCS#12 files.\nThe \u0026#34;PKCS12_item_decrypt_d2i_ex()\u0026#34; function does not check whether the oct parameter is NULL before dereferencing it. When called from\n\u0026#34;PKCS12_unpack_p7encdata()\u0026#34; with a malformed PKCS#12 file, this parameter can be NULL, causing a crash. The vulnerability is limited to Denial of Service\nand cannot be escalated to achieve code execution or memory disclosure.\n\nExploiting this issue requires an attacker to provide a malformed PKCS#12 file to an application that processes it. For that reason the issue was assessed as\nLow severity according to our Security Policy.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the PKCS#12 implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary.\n\nOpenSSL versions 3.6 prior to 3.6.1, 3.5 prior to 3.5.5, 3.4 prior to 3.4.4, 3.3 prior to 3.3.6, 3.0 prior to 3.0.19, 1.1.1.x and 1.0.2.x are vulnerable to this issue.","markdown":"Issue summary: Processing a malformed PKCS#12 file can trigger a NULL Pointer Dereference in the \u0026#34;PKCS12_item_decrypt_d2i_ex()\u0026#34; function.\n\nImpact summary: A NULL pointer dereference can trigger a crash which leads to Denial of Service for an application processing PKCS#12 files.\nThe \u0026#34;PKCS12_item_decrypt_d2i_ex()\u0026#34; function does not check whether the oct parameter is NULL before dereferencing it. When called from\n\u0026#34;PKCS12_unpack_p7encdata()\u0026#34; with a malformed PKCS#12 file, this parameter can be NULL, causing a crash. The vulnerability is limited to Denial of Service\nand cannot be escalated to achieve code execution or memory disclosure.\n\nExploiting this issue requires an attacker to provide a malformed PKCS#12 file to an application that processes it. For that reason the issue was assessed as\nLow severity according to our Security Policy.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the PKCS#12 implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary.\n\nOpenSSL versions 3.6 prior to 3.6.1, 3.5 prior to 3.5.5, 3.4 prior to 3.4.4, 3.3 prior to 3.3.6, 3.0 prior to 3.0.19, 1.1.1.x and 1.0.2.x are vulnerable to this issue."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Issue summary: Processing a malformed PKCS#12 file can trigger a NULL Pointer Dereference in the \u0026#34;PKCS12_item_decrypt_d2i_ex()\u0026#34; function.\n\nImpact summary: A NULL pointer dereference can trigger a crash which leads to Denial of Service for an application processing PKCS#12 files.\nThe \u0026#34;PKCS12_item_decrypt_d2i_ex()\u0026#34; function does not check whether the oct parameter is NULL before dereferencing it. When called from\n\u0026#34;PKCS12_unpack_p7encdata()\u0026#34; with a malformed PKCS#12 file, this parameter can be NULL, causing a crash. The vulnerability is limited to Denial of Service\nand cannot be escalated to achieve code execution or memory disclosure.\n\nExploiting this issue requires an attacker to provide a malformed PKCS#12 file to an application that processes it. For that reason the issue was assessed as\nLow severity according to our Security Policy.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the PKCS#12 implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary.\n\nOpenSSL versions 3.6 prior to 3.6.1, 3.5 prior to 3.5.5, 3.4 prior to 3.4.4, 3.3 prior to 3.3.6, 3.0 prior to 3.0.19, 1.1.1.x and 1.0.2.x are vulnerable to this issue."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202569421","id":"CVE-2025-69421 (containers)","description":"Issue summary: Processing a malformed PKCS#12 file can trigger a NULL Pointer Dereference in the \u0026#34;PKCS12_item_decrypt_d2i_ex()\u0026#34; function.\n\nImpact summary: A NULL pointer dereference can trigger a crash which leads to Denial of Service for an application processing PKCS#12 files.\nThe \u0026#34;PKCS12_item_decrypt_d2i_ex()\u0026#34; function does not check whether the oct parameter is NULL before dereferencing it. When called from\n\u0026#34;PKCS12_unpack_p7encdata()\u0026#34; with a malformed PKCS#12 file, this parameter can be NULL, causing a crash. The vulnerability is limited to Denial of Service\nand cannot be escalated to achieve code execution or memory disclosure.\n\nExploiting this issue requires an attacker to provide a malformed PKCS#12 file to an application that processes it. For that reason the issue was assessed as\nLow severity according to our Security Policy.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.6, 3.5, 3.4, 3.3 and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the PKCS#12 implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary.\n\nOpenSSL versions 3.6 prior to 3.6.1, 3.5 prior to 3.5.5, 3.4 prior to 3.4.4, 3.3 prior to 3.3.6, 3.0 prior to 3.0.19, 1.1.1.x and 1.0.2.x are vulnerable to this issue.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-9230 (containers)","name":"Cve20259230","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"An application trying to decrypt CMS messages encrypted using password-based encryption can trigger an out-of-bounds read and write. This out-of-bounds read may trigger a crash, which leads to a Denial of Service for an application. The out-of-bounds write can cause memory corruption, which can have various consequences, including a Denial of Service or execution of attacker-supplied code. Although the consequences of a successful exploit of this vulnerability could be severe, the probability that the attacker would be able to perform it is low. Besides, password-based (PWRI) encryption support in CMS messages is very rarely used. For that reason, the issue was assessed as Moderate severity according to our Security Policy.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.5, 3.4, 3.3, 3.2, 3.1, and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the CMS implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary. This issue affects OpenSSL versions 1.0.1-beta1 through 3.0.17, 3.1.0-alpha1 through 3.2.5, 3.3.0-alpha1 through 3.3.4, 3.4.0-alpha1 through 3.4.2, and 3.5.0-alpha1 through 3.5.3, 3.6.0-alpha1 through 3.6.0-beta1.","markdown":"An application trying to decrypt CMS messages encrypted using password-based encryption can trigger an out-of-bounds read and write. This out-of-bounds read may trigger a crash, which leads to a Denial of Service for an application. The out-of-bounds write can cause memory corruption, which can have various consequences, including a Denial of Service or execution of attacker-supplied code. Although the consequences of a successful exploit of this vulnerability could be severe, the probability that the attacker would be able to perform it is low. Besides, password-based (PWRI) encryption support in CMS messages is very rarely used. For that reason, the issue was assessed as Moderate severity according to our Security Policy.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.5, 3.4, 3.3, 3.2, 3.1, and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the CMS implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary. This issue affects OpenSSL versions 1.0.1-beta1 through 3.0.17, 3.1.0-alpha1 through 3.2.5, 3.3.0-alpha1 through 3.3.4, 3.4.0-alpha1 through 3.4.2, and 3.5.0-alpha1 through 3.5.3, 3.6.0-alpha1 through 3.6.0-beta1."},"fullDescription":{"text":"An application trying to decrypt CMS messages encrypted using password-based encryption can trigger an out-of-bounds read and write. This out-of-bounds read may trigger a crash, which leads to a Denial of Service for an application. The out-of-bounds write can cause memory corruption, which can have various consequences, including a Denial of Service or execution of attacker-supplied code. Although the consequences of a successful exploit of this vulnerability could be severe, the probability that the attacker would be able to perform it is low. Besides, password-based (PWRI) encryption support in CMS messages is very rarely used. For that reason, the issue was assessed as Moderate severity according to our Security Policy.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.5, 3.4, 3.3, 3.2, 3.1, and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the CMS implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary. This issue affects OpenSSL versions 1.0.1-beta1 through 3.0.17, 3.1.0-alpha1 through 3.2.5, 3.3.0-alpha1 through 3.3.4, 3.4.0-alpha1 through 3.4.2, and 3.5.0-alpha1 through 3.5.3, 3.6.0-alpha1 through 3.6.0-beta1."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve20259230","id":"CVE-2025-9230 (containers)","description":"An application trying to decrypt CMS messages encrypted using password-based encryption can trigger an out-of-bounds read and write. This out-of-bounds read may trigger a crash, which leads to a Denial of Service for an application. The out-of-bounds write can cause memory corruption, which can have various consequences, including a Denial of Service or execution of attacker-supplied code. Although the consequences of a successful exploit of this vulnerability could be severe, the probability that the attacker would be able to perform it is low. Besides, password-based (PWRI) encryption support in CMS messages is very rarely used. For that reason, the issue was assessed as Moderate severity according to our Security Policy.\n\nThe FIPS modules in 3.5, 3.4, 3.3, 3.2, 3.1, and 3.0 are not affected by this issue, as the CMS implementation is outside the OpenSSL FIPS module boundary. This issue affects OpenSSL versions 1.0.1-beta1 through 3.0.17, 3.1.0-alpha1 through 3.2.5, 3.3.0-alpha1 through 3.3.4, 3.4.0-alpha1 through 3.4.2, and 3.5.0-alpha1 through 3.5.3, 3.6.0-alpha1 through 3.6.0-beta1.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2018-5709 (containers)","name":"Cve20185709","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"An issue was discovered in MIT Kerberos 5 (aka krb5) through 1.16. There is a variable \u0026#34;dbentry-\u0026gt;n_key_data\u0026#34; in kadmin/dbutil/dump.c that can store 16-bit data but unknowingly the developer has assigned a \u0026#34;u4\u0026#34; variable to it, which is for 32-bit data. An attacker can use this vulnerability to affect other artifacts of the database as we know that a Kerberos database dump file contains trusted data.","markdown":"An issue was discovered in MIT Kerberos 5 (aka krb5) through 1.16. There is a variable \u0026#34;dbentry-\u0026gt;n_key_data\u0026#34; in kadmin/dbutil/dump.c that can store 16-bit data but unknowingly the developer has assigned a \u0026#34;u4\u0026#34; variable to it, which is for 32-bit data. An attacker can use this vulnerability to affect other artifacts of the database as we know that a Kerberos database dump file contains trusted data."},"fullDescription":{"text":"An issue was discovered in MIT Kerberos 5 (aka krb5) through 1.16. There is a variable \u0026#34;dbentry-\u0026gt;n_key_data\u0026#34; in kadmin/dbutil/dump.c that can store 16-bit data but unknowingly the developer has assigned a \u0026#34;u4\u0026#34; variable to it, which is for 32-bit data. An attacker can use this vulnerability to affect other artifacts of the database as we know that a Kerberos database dump file contains trusted data."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve20185709","id":"CVE-2018-5709 (containers)","description":"An issue was discovered in MIT Kerberos 5 (aka krb5) through 1.16. There is a variable \u0026#34;dbentry-\u0026gt;n_key_data\u0026#34; in kadmin/dbutil/dump.c that can store 16-bit data but unknowingly the developer has assigned a \u0026#34;u4\u0026#34; variable to it, which is for 32-bit data. An attacker can use this vulnerability to affect other artifacts of the database as we know that a Kerberos database dump file contains trusted data.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2022-4899 (containers)","name":"Cve20224899","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"A vulnerability was found in zstd versions prior to 1.5.4, where an attacker can supply an empty string as an argument to the command line tool to cause a buffer overrun.","markdown":"A vulnerability was found in zstd versions prior to 1.5.4, where an attacker can supply an empty string as an argument to the command line tool to cause a buffer overrun."},"fullDescription":{"text":"A vulnerability was found in zstd versions prior to 1.5.4, where an attacker can supply an empty string as an argument to the command line tool to cause a buffer overrun."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve20224899","id":"CVE-2022-4899 (containers)","description":"A vulnerability was found in zstd versions prior to 1.5.4, where an attacker can supply an empty string as an argument to the command line tool to cause a buffer overrun.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-69720 (containers)","name":"Cve202569720","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The infocmp command-line tool in ncurses has a Stack-based Buffer Overflow in \u0026#34;analyze_string\u0026#34; in \u0026#34;progs/infocmp.c\u0026#34;.","markdown":"The infocmp command-line tool in ncurses has a Stack-based Buffer Overflow in \u0026#34;analyze_string\u0026#34; in \u0026#34;progs/infocmp.c\u0026#34;."},"fullDescription":{"text":"The infocmp command-line tool in ncurses has a Stack-based Buffer Overflow in \u0026#34;analyze_string\u0026#34; in \u0026#34;progs/infocmp.c\u0026#34;."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202569720","id":"CVE-2025-69720 (containers)","description":"The infocmp command-line tool in ncurses has a Stack-based Buffer Overflow in \u0026#34;analyze_string\u0026#34; in \u0026#34;progs/infocmp.c\u0026#34;.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2024-41996 (containers)","name":"Cve202441996","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Validating the order of the public keys in the Diffie-Hellman Key Agreement Protocol, when an approved safe prime is used, allows remote attackers (from the client side) to trigger unnecessarily expensive server-side DHE modular-exponentiation calculations. The client may cause asymmetric resource consumption. The basic attack scenario is that the client must claim that it can only communicate with DHE, and the server must be configured to allow DHE and validate the order of the public key. This issue affects OpenSSL versions prior to openssl-3.4.0-alpha1.","markdown":"Validating the order of the public keys in the Diffie-Hellman Key Agreement Protocol, when an approved safe prime is used, allows remote attackers (from the client side) to trigger unnecessarily expensive server-side DHE modular-exponentiation calculations. The client may cause asymmetric resource consumption. The basic attack scenario is that the client must claim that it can only communicate with DHE, and the server must be configured to allow DHE and validate the order of the public key. This issue affects OpenSSL versions prior to openssl-3.4.0-alpha1."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Validating the order of the public keys in the Diffie-Hellman Key Agreement Protocol, when an approved safe prime is used, allows remote attackers (from the client side) to trigger unnecessarily expensive server-side DHE modular-exponentiation calculations. The client may cause asymmetric resource consumption. The basic attack scenario is that the client must claim that it can only communicate with DHE, and the server must be configured to allow DHE and validate the order of the public key. This issue affects OpenSSL versions prior to openssl-3.4.0-alpha1."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202441996","id":"CVE-2024-41996 (containers)","description":"Validating the order of the public keys in the Diffie-Hellman Key Agreement Protocol, when an approved safe prime is used, allows remote attackers (from the client side) to trigger unnecessarily expensive server-side DHE modular-exponentiation calculations. The client may cause asymmetric resource consumption. The basic attack scenario is that the client must claim that it can only communicate with DHE, and the server must be configured to allow DHE and validate the order of the public key. This issue affects OpenSSL versions prior to openssl-3.4.0-alpha1.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2025-8941 (containers)","name":"Cve20258941","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"A flaw was found in linux-pam. The pam_namespace module may improperly handle user-controlled paths, allowing local users to exploit symlink attacks and race conditions to elevate their privileges to root. This CVE provides a \u0026#34;complete\u0026#34; fix for CVE-2025-6020.","markdown":"A flaw was found in linux-pam. The pam_namespace module may improperly handle user-controlled paths, allowing local users to exploit symlink attacks and race conditions to elevate their privileges to root. This CVE provides a \u0026#34;complete\u0026#34; fix for CVE-2025-6020."},"fullDescription":{"text":"A flaw was found in linux-pam. The pam_namespace module may improperly handle user-controlled paths, allowing local users to exploit symlink attacks and race conditions to elevate their privileges to root. This CVE provides a \u0026#34;complete\u0026#34; fix for CVE-2025-6020."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve20258941","id":"CVE-2025-8941 (containers)","description":"A flaw was found in linux-pam. The pam_namespace module may improperly handle user-controlled paths, allowing local users to exploit symlink attacks and race conditions to elevate their privileges to root. This CVE provides a \u0026#34;complete\u0026#34; fix for CVE-2025-6020.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2017-11164 (containers)","name":"Cve201711164","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"In PCRE 8.41, the OP_KETRMAX feature in the match function in pcre_exec.c allows stack exhaustion (uncontrolled recursion) when processing a crafted regular expression.","markdown":"In PCRE 8.41, the OP_KETRMAX feature in the match function in pcre_exec.c allows stack exhaustion (uncontrolled recursion) when processing a crafted regular expression."},"fullDescription":{"text":"In PCRE 8.41, the OP_KETRMAX feature in the match function in pcre_exec.c allows stack exhaustion (uncontrolled recursion) when processing a crafted regular expression."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve201711164","id":"CVE-2017-11164 (containers)","description":"In PCRE 8.41, the OP_KETRMAX feature in the match function in pcre_exec.c allows stack exhaustion (uncontrolled recursion) when processing a crafted regular expression.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"CVE-2026-24882 (containers)","name":"Cve202624882","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"In GnuPG before 2.5.17, a stack-based buffer overflow exists in tpm2daemon during handling of the PKDECRYPT command for TPM-backed RSA and ECC keys.","markdown":"In GnuPG before 2.5.17, a stack-based buffer overflow exists in tpm2daemon during handling of the PKDECRYPT command for TPM-backed RSA and ECC keys."},"fullDescription":{"text":"In GnuPG before 2.5.17, a stack-based buffer overflow exists in tpm2daemon during handling of the PKDECRYPT command for TPM-backed RSA and ECC keys."},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Cve202624882","id":"CVE-2026-24882 (containers)","description":"In GnuPG before 2.5.17, a stack-based buffer overflow exists in tpm2daemon during handling of the PKDECRYPT command for TPM-backed RSA and ECC keys.","tags":["security","checkmarx","containers"]}},{"id":"Docker Socket Mounted In Container - d6355c88-1e8d-49e9-b2f2-f8a1ca12c75b [Taken from query_id] (kics)","name":"Docker Socket Mounted In Container","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Docker socket docker.sock should not be mounted on host. If the docker socket is mounted, it can allow its processes to execute docker commands. Value: There is a docker socket named 'docker.sock' mounted in a volume Excepted value: To not have docker socket named 'docker.sock' mounted in a volume","markdown":"Docker socket docker.sock should not be mounted on host. If the docker socket is mounted, it can allow its processes to execute docker commands. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eValue:\u003c/strong\u003e There is a docker socket named 'docker.sock' mounted in a volume \u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExcepted value:\u003c/strong\u003e To not have docker socket named 'docker.sock' mounted in a volume"},"fullDescription":{"text":"Docker socket docker.sock should not be mounted on host. If the docker socket is mounted, it can allow its processes to execute docker commands. Value: There is a docker socket named 'docker.sock' mounted in a volume Excepted value: To not have docker socket named 'docker.sock' mounted in a volume"},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Docker Socket Mounted In Container","id":"Docker Socket Mounted In Container - d6355c88-1e8d-49e9-b2f2-f8a1ca12c75b [Taken from query_id] (kics)","description":"Docker socket docker.sock should not be mounted on host. If the docker socket is mounted, it can allow its processes to execute docker commands. Value: There is a docker socket named 'docker.sock' mounted in a volume Excepted value: To not have docker socket named 'docker.sock' mounted in a volume","tags":["security","checkmarx","kics"]}},{"id":"Deserialization of Untrusted Data - 9372117855007485824 (sast)","name":"Deserialization of Untrusted Data","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The serialized object read processed in test_merge_conversation_stats_success_non_overlapping in the file /tests/unit/test_conversation_stats.py at line 542 is deserialized by loads in the file /tests/unit/test_conversation_stats.py at line 544.\n\n","markdown":"The serialized object read processed in test_merge_conversation_stats_success_non_overlapping in the file /tests/unit/test_conversation_stats.py at line 542 is deserialized by loads in the file /tests/unit/test_conversation_stats.py at line 544.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"The serialized object read processed in test_merge_conversation_stats_success_non_overlapping in the file /tests/unit/test_conversation_stats.py at line 542 is deserialized by loads in the file /tests/unit/test_conversation_stats.py at line 544.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name":"Deserialization of Untrusted Data","id":"Deserialization of Untrusted Data - 9372117855007485824 (sast)","description":"The serialized object read processed in test_merge_conversation_stats_success_non_overlapping in the file /tests/unit/test_conversation_stats.py at line 542 is deserialized by loads in the file /tests/unit/test_conversation_stats.py at line 544.\n\n","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"Authenticated-Url - 98e88a4f-4b7d-4c56-a6fa-9835dfb7c8d7 (sscs-secret-detection)","name":"Authenticated-Url","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"Remove the authenticated URL username:password from source control and store it in your organization’s secret manager (e.g., AWS Secrets Manager, Azure Key Vault, HashiCorp Vault).","markdown":"Remove the authenticated URL username:password from source control and store it in your organization’s secret manager (e.g., AWS Secrets Manager, Azure Key Vault, HashiCorp Vault)."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Identify username:password inside URLS"},"properties":{"security-severity":"7.0","name